Terence's first comedy, the Andria, was produced 166 ne. Suetonius relates that when this play was offered to the Aediles, the young author was told to submit it to the judgment of Caecilius. Terence arrived when the veteran poet was at supper, and being in mean attire was seated on a stool near the table. ’ But he had read no more than a few lines, when Caecilius bade him take a place upon his couch, and bestowed high commenda- tion on the play. As Caecilius died in 168 Β. c., the Andria must have been in manuscript at least two years before its per- fonnance, and some colour is given to the above anecdote by the mention which Terence makes in the Prologue of the ill· natured criticisms of Luscius Lanuvinus.
